The story that the James J. Leahy family was told 1 CONC discussed four Leahy brothers who came to the US and then lost track of 1 CONC one another. The fact that no other brothers have yet to be tracked down 1 CONC makes this story seem unlikely. 1 CONT We do know that David Leahy, his wife Margaret, and three small children 1 CONC (John, David and Mary) were accompanied by one other adult and two other 1 CONC children. This grouping of people is based on the copy of the Passengers' 1 CONC Check Ticket (copy sent from Neal Leahy, 24 OCT 1967), issued for the 1 CONC Garrick, which sailed from Liverpool 6 DEC 1847 and arrived in New York 1 CONC 20 JAN 1848. The ticket lists five souls (children) and three adults. 1 CONT 1 CONT A review of the Garrick's passenger list (found in The Famine Immigrants: 1 CONC Lists of Irish Immigrants Arriving at the Port of New York, 1846-1851, 1 CONC vol. 2: July 1847-June 1848, pp. 214-15, edited by Ira Glazier, assisted 1 CONC by Michael Teppir, [Baltimore: Geneological Publishing Company, Inc.]), 1 CONC suggests the other members of the Leahy party were Mary Murphy and her 1 CONC children, Mary and Johanna. In addition to these three Murphys, there are 1 CONC four other Murphy entries listed on the list: Pat Murphy (accompanied by 1 CONC Bridget), Anne Murphy, Mary Murphy and another Pat Murphy. No other 1 CONC Leahys are listed on the passenger list. 1 CONT 1 CONT Jody L. Filipi sends along the following additional information on the 1 CONC GARRICK: It was a 3-masted, square-rigged ship, built in New York in 1836 1 CONC by the firm of Brown & Bell. 895 tons, 157' 6" x 35' 4" x 21' (length x 1 CONC beam x depth of hold). She served in the Liverpool Dramatic Line from 1 CONC 1837 to 1853, then in James Foster, Jr's Liverpool "line" until 1856. The 1 CONC GARRICK was the fastest packet of her generation, and during her packet 1 CONC line career her average westbound passage was 32 days, her shortest being 1 CONC 18 days, her longest 54 days [Robert Greenhalgh Albion, Square-Riggers on 1 CONC Schedule; The New York Sailing Packets to England, France, and the Cotton 1 CONC Ports (Princeton: Princeton University, pp. 280-281]. [Posted to the 1 CONC Emigration-Ships List by Michael Palmer - 30 October 1997] 1 CONT 1 CONT Another point of controversy in the family lore has to do with David's 1 CONC daughter, Mary, who is buried in Pawtucket. The story goes that Mary died 1 CONC a day out from port (New York), and that Margaret didn't want the child's 1 CONC body dumped at sea. The family pretended the child was sleeping until 1 CONC getting to shore, where the child was buried. Again, according to family 1 CONC lore, it was the family's secrecy surrounding the death of Mary Leahy 1 CONC while still at sea which caused a rift between the David Leahys and other 1 CONC members of the clan travelling with them to the US. This portion of the 1 CONC story may be true; but if it is, the rift was between Leahys and Murphys 1 CONC rather than between David Leahy and his brothers as the story has always 1 CONC been told. 1 CONT 1 CONT 1 CONT ------------------- 1 CONT Thank you for your enquiry. The Town of Watergrasshill is in the civil 1 CONC parishes of Ardnageehy & Kilquane (R.C. parish Watergrasshill) in East 1 CONC Cork. Records start there in 1836. 1 CONT 1 CONT 1855 WI State Census ID# WI00314101 1 CONT Mosel, Sheboygan County, WI 1 CONT David Leahy 1 CONT 1 CONT 1860 WI Federal Census ID# WI456110019 1 CONT Abbott, Sheboygan County, WI, page 004 1 CONT David Leahy 1 CONT 1 CONT According to Census data from 1766, Docese of Cloyne (information 1 CONC transcribed from public records by Magaret Moon), there are several 1 CONC parished within County Cork from which our branch of Leahys may have 1 CONC sprung. We lived on 31st and 1 CONC Lincoln Blvd. In Omaha, NE when his travel to or from Guam (I'm not sure 1 CONC which way he was going) brought him through Omaha.* 1 CONT It's hard to believe that Paul was my Grandpa (Justin D.) Leahy's 1 CONC brother. He was 12 ½ years younger, which explained some of the 1 CONC differences. But the two were studies in contrast: I remember Uncle 1 CONC Paul laughing or smiling most of the time. He always seemed happy to see 1 CONC Dad and Mom and all of the family-even me. He always remembered my 1 CONC name. He never complained about the noise my siblings and I created. I 1 CONC don't remember Grandpa Leahy finding life amusing, he rarely seemed happy 1 CONC to see me or my brothers or sisters, and he paid us money to be quiet or 1 CONC go outside and play. He didn't even know which of us I was half the time. 1 CONT Because Paul was always traveling on military business, he was 1 CONC always in uniform. He looked pretty sharp, too. But that didn't keep 1 CONC him from getting down on the floor and playing with us. He had a way of 1 CONC making us feel special which I don't think I felt with any other uncle 1 CONC (except my mom's step brother, Dave Vant) 1 CONT - - - 1 CONT *My sister Jody thinks Paul may have been stationed at Fort Omaha at this 1 CONC time. I kind of doubt it because we didn't see him but a few times over 1 CONC the span of a week or so the way I remember it.--RMLeahy 1 CONT _________ 1 CONT 1 CONT 1 CONT 1 CONT Information on P. Paul F. Leahy, 59, a former Port Washington dentist was fatally 1 CONC burned in an automobile accident last week Wednesday on the island of 1 CONC Guam where he was stationed with the United States Navy. 1 CONT 1 CONT Capt. Leahy, a native of Random Lake, was alone in the automobile when 1 CONC the accident happened on the Agana naval air station, according to word 1 CONC received here. His wife Maybelle had been with her husband during the 1 1 CONC 1/2 years he was stationed there. 1 CONT 1 CONT After practicing dentistry here since the 1930's, Capt. Leahy served in 1 CONC the navy during World War II, and was recalled during the Korean 1 CONC conflict. He remained in the service and was stationed at the Great Lakes 1 CONC (Ill.) training center, in Tokyo and in California before going to Guam. 1 CONC The family lived here until about three years ago. 1 CONT 1 CONT Son and Two Daughters 1 CONT 1 CONT Survivors besides his wife include a son, Paul Jr., who was living at 1 CONC Madison, and two daughters, Mrs. Ann Vandre, of Lake Mills, Wis., and 1 CONC Mrs. Lois Monahan of Mazomanie, Wis. 1 CONT 1 CONT The navy informed family members that the body would be returned to St. 1 CONC Paul, Minn. 1 CONT 1 CONT Funeral services will be held at 10 a.m. Friday at Bloomington, Minn., 1 CONC with interment at Fort Snelling, U.S. Navy cemetery, St. Paul, Minn. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT Navy Man's Body Being Sent Here 1 CONT 1 CONT Agana, Guam--The charred body of a man found Wednesday in a burned car 1 CONC was identified today as that of Navy Capt. Paul F. Leahy, senior dental 1 CONC officer at the naval air station on Guam. 1 CONT 1 CONT The body will leave Guam Saturday en route to St. Paul for burial. 1 CONC Leahy's hometown was not given. 1 CONT 1 CONT The Twin Cities naval air station had no record of an officer of this 1 CONC name. 1 CONT 1 CONT --probably from a Port Washington newspaper; none of three sources 1 CONC specifically identified. 1 CONT [from papers of Anne C. (Spellman) Leahy; 1 CONT courtesy of Jody (Leahy) Filipi] 1 CONT 1 CONT ---------------------------- 1 CONT 1 CONT [Dr. Paul Leahy] Tells of 25 Months in Japan 1 CONT Port Washington[, WI] @@1955 1 CONT 1 CONT If you want a tooth pulled, please don't go to Dr. Paul Leahy. He's on 1 CONC vacation after 25 months with the Navy in Japan. 1 CONT 1 CONT Cdr. Leahy, a navy dentist, is spending a month's leave with his family 1 CONC at his home at 116 W. Pierre Lane before reporting to his next base at 1 CONC Great Lakes. 1 CONT 1 CONT A native of Random Lake, Dr. Leahy had a dental office in Port Washington 1 CONC until he was called back into the navy in 1950. He had served during 1 CONC World War II, entering the navy in 1942. 1 CONT 1 CONT Cdr. Leahy spent his two years in Japan at Yokosuka naval base near 1 CONC Yokohama. An old Japanese naval base, the U. S. has a 99-year lease to 1 CONC the base and uses it for ship repair and [as a] supply station. Almost 1 CONC all the employees on the base are Japanese--between 15 and 18,000. 1 CONT 1 CONT Dr. Leahy says there is no comparing Japan and the United States. 1 CONC "There's more room here. Japan is so crowded," he reported. He pointed 1 CONC out that if you put half the people in the United States in the state of 1 CONC Wisconsin you would have an environment similar to Japan. 1 CONT 1 CONT "The Japanese people are very nice--and hard working," Dr. Leahy said. 1 CONC "They are not asking for anything. We're giving it to them because we 1 CONC know we have to have them on our side." He added the Japanese had almost 1 CONC rebuilt all of the World War II damage. 1 CONT 1 CONT Mrs. Leahy added that after a few days in the country the Japanese eyes 1 CONC don't even slant any more. Mrs. Leahy and their son Skipper spent three 1 CONC months in 1953 visiting Cdr. Leahy in Japan. They were fortunate to be 1 CONC there when their son-in-law Pat Monahan and neighbor Jim Duff were also 1 CONC there. 1 CONT During their visit they lived in a Japanese home in Kamakura, about 10 1 CONC miles from the naval base. Skipper attended school at the base and had 1 CONC several Japanese teachers. He best remembers the Japanese fairy tales one 1 CONC teacher told the American students. Dr. Leahy was impressed by the 1 CONC Japanese education system. Children attend classes six days a week and 1 CONC have only a month of vacation in the summer. 1 CONT 1 CONT Living 10 miles from the base resulted in several expert observations of 1 CONC the Japanese transportation system. Dr. Leahy believes the Japanese 1 CONC electric train system is the best in the world. "The trains are clean, 1 CONC fast, on time, and there are a lot of them." 1 CONT 1 CONT Road transportation, however, is a very different story. "In Japan, you 1 CONC don't ask how far it is, you ask how long it takes," Dr. Leahy reports. 1 CONC It often took the Leahys several hours to travel the mere ten miles from 1 CONC the base to their home. 1 CONT 1 CONT "There's so much traffic, so slow moving, people crossing all around and 1 CONC a lot of three-wheel motorcycle trucks." 1 CONT 1 CONT When Cdr. Leahy arrived back in the U. S., he reports, his biggest 1 CONC adjustment was to the speed of the American traffic. It took several days 1 CONC to get used to U. S. traffic habits. He did it by driving home to Port 1 CONC [Washington] from California. 0 @I0019@ INDI 1 NAME Martha Juanita /Hinson/ 1 SEX F 1 BIRT 2 PLAC See masterfile 1 FAMS @F0491@ 0 @I0021@ INDI 1 NAME Daniel /Burk/ 2 SOUR @S04038@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT Date of Import: Nov 3, 1999 2 SOUR @S04041@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT Date of Import: Nov 4, 1999 1 SEX M 1 FAMS @F0008@ 1 NOTE @NI0021@ 0 @NI0021@ NOTE 1 CONC Father's name from Christening record of Catherine Burke (spelled BURK) 1 CONC from FAMILYSEARCH.ORG, Summer 1999. 0 @I0022@ INDI 1 NAME Ilynn Marie /Vandre/ 2 SOUR @S04038@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT Date of Import: Nov 3, 1999 2 SOUR @S04041@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT Date of Import: Nov 4, 1999 1 SEX F 1 BIRT 2 DATE 6 OCT 1965 2 PLAC Port Washington, Ozuakee County, WI 2 SOUR @S04038@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT Date of Import: Nov 3, 1999 2 SOUR @S04041@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT Date of Import: Nov 4, 1999 1 FAMS @F0009@ 1 FAMC @F0002@ 1 NOTE @NI0022@ 0 @NI0022@ NOTE 1 CONC Not sure of the first name; it may be LYNN. Navy Cemetery, St. Paul, MN 1 FAMS @F0007@ 1 FAMC @F0687@ 1 NOTE @NI0027@ 0 @NI0027@ NOTE 1 CONC WI Births 1820-1907, Ancestry.com 5 JAN 2001: 1 CONT Milwaukee 1 CONT Reel #0203 // Record #001531 1 CONT 1 CONT _____________ 1 CONT Maybelle Hayeland Leahy 1 CONT One of my fondest memories of Maybelle comes from her extended visit with 1 CONC our family when my older sister, Jody, married. Back in those days (mid 1 CONC 70s), I was a college man, but when I came home, I did a lot of the 1 CONC cooking (a chore I sort of took over in 8th grade when Mom went back to 1 CONC work). My little sister, Marcia, was especially fond of my oatmeal 1 CONC cookies (with or without raisins, with or without chocolate, with or 1 CONC without peanut butter). As it turns out, Maybelle was, too. She told me 1 CONC she especially liked the fact that my cookies weren't small. Of the 1 CONC adult females I knew, only Grandma Vant (Mom's mother) thought big 1 CONC cookies were a good deal. How could I not like a woman who liked my big 1 CONC cookies? 1 CONT Maybelle and I wrote back and forth from then on. But it wasn't 1 CONC until about the time I got married that we ever really spent much time 1 CONC talking on the phone. But, she told me, it's so much easier to call than 1 CONC to write-which is true. And from then on, until her heart attack, we 1 CONC talked quite often. After her heart attack, the calls were fewer. She 1 CONC always told me I needed to come down and visit her in Mercedes. 1 CONC Unfortunately, I never did. I wish I had. And I miss our phone calls. 1 CONT My sister Jody says what she remembers most about Maybelle was how 1 CONC nice she was and how funny.--RMLeahy 1 CONT _____________ 1 CONT 1 CONT According to Charles Hayeland (phone conversation 23 JAN 2001), Maybelle 1 CONC returned to WI in 2000 at Navy expense for medical treatment. She moved 1 CONC into a Lake Mills nursing home (near her daughter, Anne). She was 1 CONC cremated, and she is buried with Paul at Fort Snelling Navy Cemetery in 1 CONC St. Paul, MN. 1 CONT 1 CONT In a letter dated 26 FEB 2000, Charles Hayeland writes that Maybelle died 1 CONC 6 NOV 2000. 1 CONT 1 CONT -------------------------- 1 CONT 1 CONT Letters from Maybelle to her sister- and brother-in-law, Anne C. 1 CONC (Spellman) and Justin Leahy 1 CONT (courtesy of Jody (Leahy) Filipi) 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 8 July [1963] Mon. 9 P.M. 1 CONT 1 CONT Dear Anna and Justin: 1 CONT 1 CONT They have a saying over here, "Guam is Good"--I think it's fabulous!! 1 CONC There are still signs of Typhoon Karen, but it's amazing all the 1 CONC rebuilding they've done. 1 CONT 1 CONT Our jet flight was delightful and we enjoyed the two hours at the 1 CONC international airport in Honolulu. We cruised along at 575 miler per, at 1 CONC an altitude up to 37,000 ft. and the temp. below us was up to 42 degrees 1 CONC below zero. I could harly contain myself when I saw the lights of 1 CONC Guam--and knew Paul was waiting--he and the "Aloha" committee, about 15 1 CONC couples. I got my first leis from him and, I guess, in all I was wearing 1 CONC about 7 or 8 leis. The teenagers were on hand to welcome Skipper and he, 1 CONC too, was wearing 5 or 6 leis. They whisked him away shortly, and Paul 1 CONC invited up to our home for a drink. They could only stay an hour or so 1 CONC and then they had to go back to the terminal to say "Farewell" to those 1 CONC leaving at midnight for the states. But Skip, Paul and I visited until 2 1 CONC or 3 A.M. 1 CONT 1 CONT Our home is very comfortable with large rooms--3 bedrooms, 1 bath, living 1 CONC room, dining room and kitchen. Skip thinks our kitchen looks like an 1 CONC appliance store. Beautiful landscaping--doesn't seem like quarters on a 1 CONC base. No more weeding. Captains rate a gardner. Paul had our quarters 1 CONC fully air-conditioned. 1 CONT 1 CONT The social whirl started the next nite and sometimes I wonder if it will 1 CONC ever cease--cocktail parties, dinners, coffees and a change-of-command 1 CONC ceremony and reception where we met the Gov. of Guam and his wife. The 1 CONC new captain of the base lives across the street and this is his third 1 CONC tour of duty in Guam. His wife lived here with him 13 years ago and, 1 CONC from all reports, it was very rugged then. Everyone is so considerate 1 CONC and friendly and living and entertaining is very casual--that's my speed. 1 CONT 1 CONT Bridge every Thursday 8:30 AM to 11:30 AM, so I'll try it this 1 CONC week--would also like to try golf--they are giving lessons now but so far 1 CONC can't manage to crowd it into my schedule--and poor Paul has to WORK. 1 CONT 1 CONT We've tried the restaurants in Agana, and the food is excellent. Several 1 CONC Chinese places. 1 CONT 1 CONT Skip was only on the island four days when he talked his dad into buying 1 CONC him a motorbike. He was swimming in the ocean today with fins, snorkel, 1 CONC etc. He is really having a ball. 1 CONT 1 CONT We have the most beautiful view from our our dining room of the sunset 1 CONC over the Philipine Sea. Oh, I am sure you would love this island as much 1 CONC as I do. Will be writing more later, but would love to hear from you 1 CONC when you have time. Love from Paul and Maybelle 1 CONT 1 CONT New Address: 1 CONT Capt. and Mrs. Paul F. Leahy 1 CONT 416 W. Sunset Blvd. 1 CONT US NAS Navy #943 1 CONT c/o FPO San Francisco, CA 1 CONT 1 CONT We have mail delivery to the house. 1 CONT 1 CONT Now I have to guess at your address--my address book is in household 1 CONC effects. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT 18 JAN '64 Saturday 1 CONT 1 CONT Dear Anne and Justin: 1 CONT 1 CONT Your Christmas card is beautiful--even the name "Leahy" instead of 1 CONC "Hallmark" on the back made it exciting. Hope you got to Bob's for Xmas 1 CONC as you had planned 'cause it isn't much fun without young people to make 1 CONC things merry. 1 CONT 1 CONT Paul has been in and out of the hospital this last month. He was 1 CONC admitted 17 Dec. and they gave him all the tests in the book and x-rays 1 CONC and then on 26 Dec. they did a thyroid exploratory and discovered his 1 CONC thyroid is off-center to the right, plus adhesions from 1944 New Guinea 1 CONC pleurisy and a thickened big heart artery which showed up as a mass on 1 CONC the film. We were grateful they didn't need to do any more surgery, also 1 CONC to know "no malignancy" however, he was very uncomfortable for a week or 1 CONC so. 1 CONT 1 CONT After all that, they discovered he had diabetes and high blood 1 CONC pressure--no medications for the diabetes only diet--1800 calories per 1 CONC day, which is plenty. He still hasn't been discharged from the hospital, 1 CONC even though he works a few hours every day at the dental clinic. 1 CONT 1 CONT Next week they are sending his medical reports to Washington, along with 1 CONC a letter from him saying he doesn't want a medical discharge for he would 1 CONC like a few more years of active duty. The medical report must be 1 CONC presented to the "board" and Paul must be present--the closest would be 1 CONC Oakland, Calif., and in order for him to appear there, they will probably 1 CONC give him orders for duty near there--and in the interim we just "sit" and 1 CONC wonder what will happen and when-- 1 CONT 1 CONT These are the same symptoms he had four years ago at Great Lakes-- 1 CONT 1 CONT Typhoon Susan was "skirting" Guam day before Xmas--we were all boarded up 1 CONC and prepared--the whole base was secured and midnite mass was 1 CONC cancelled--winds 65 mi per and torrential rains which lasted until 1 CONC Christmas afternoon. It hit Saipan. We did manage to get to mass at 1 CONC noon on Xmas Day--only three or four families there--wearing raincoats 1 CONC and rubber zorries-- We lost our electricity, so we cooked out Xmas 1 CONC dinner on the charcoal grill-- Friends kep stopping by all afternoon 1 CONC until it was time for me to take Paul up to the hospital for 5 P.M.-- 1 CONT 1 CONT Pat Monahan made a tape of two Thanksgiving dinners they attended. One 1 CONC was with his relatives, mom and dad and the grandchildren and the other 1 CONC was at my brother Frank's and Ann and family, Chas (my Dad) and Katie, 1 CONC Skipper and Pat and Lois' family were all there and Monahan is quite the 1 CONC MC-- Ann sent movies and Lois sent movies so it was almost as good as a 1 CONC visit. 1 CONT 1 CONT I started golf lessons last week and find them very enjoyable and I'm 1 CONC learning in case we have to retire--at least we can keep busy. 1 CONT 1 CONT Paul gets out in the sun everyday and has finally lost his bedroom 1 CONC pallor-- He takes me out in the "boonies" and we hunt for wood roses-- We 1 CONC found enough for two arrangements-- It's just a little early for them. 1 CONT 1 CONT "It's almost time to think about dinner-- Will keep you informed of our 1 CONC "whereabouts"-- 1 CONT 1 CONT Love to both from Maybelle and Paul 1 CONT 1 CONT --I'm sorry I forgot to mention receiving Paul's birthday card-- How come 1 CONC it wasn't an "original"? I'm kidding. Thanks for remembering. More 1 CONC Love, M. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT 16 Feb '64 1 CONT 1 CONT Dear Anna and Justin: 1 CONT 1 CONT We are going to mass at the Cathedral at 10 and will mail this at the 1 CONC P.O. The mail goes out tonite. 1 CONT 1 CONT Paul feels good and is working everyday. The hospital Drs. recommended 1 CONC to the Bureau "limited duty for him"-- That was a couple of weeks ago 1 CONC and we haven't heard anymore-- So we still don't know if hhe will go back 1 CONC to the states or finish his tour in Guam-- 1 CONT 1 CONT In the meantime, we are planning a trip to Hong Kong-- We have our name 1 CONC on the list and will go "space available" via an Air Force Plane. 20 Feb 1 CONC is the date, and they notify us 12-15 hrs ahead of time-- Several 1 CONC couples, whom we enjoy very much, have signed up, too. So, hold thumbs. 1 CONC It will only be four or five days but it will be fun. 1 CONT 1 CONT No, Great Lakes Hospital didn't find any of his troubles 4 yrs 1 CONC ago--however, at Camp Pendleton, they discovered the sugar was spilling 1 CONC over and at that time he discontinued eating desserts-- 1 CONT 1 CONT From now on, he will have to take pills for his high blood pressure and 1 CONC he is getting used to them now. For the first several weeks the pills 1 CONC really laid him low. 1 CONT 1 CONT We have limited our partying to once a week-- Capt. Miller--Hospital 1 CONC Administrator--and wife had a Valentine Party Friday nite--and we had a 1 CONC most delightful time. We passed up "Crosswinds Officers Wives" Candle 1 CONC Lite Dinner last night. Had a couple of cribbage games by ourselves--at 1 CONC home. 1 CONT 1 CONT I'm sorry I didn't send a Christmas Greeting to Bob and Bette--didnb't 1 CONC have their address when I sent the first batch and when Paul got sick, I 1 CONC never wrote anymore--missed quite a few this year. Now we have Bette's 1 CONC address--received a long letter from her and intend to write them soon. 1 CONT 1 CONT Will let you know about our trip if we go-- 1 CONT 1 CONT Love to both of you, 1 CONT 1 CONT Maybelle and Paul-- 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT Post card mailed from Hong Kong 1 CONT Front features a picture of the City Hall of Hong Kong 1 CONT Note on back: 1 CONT 1 CONT 30 Mar 1 CONT 1 CONT Easter in Hong Kong--just fabulous--entertaining, delightful, etc. 1 CONC Excellent meals, magnificent restaurants and hotels (We are at the Hilton 1 CONC HK) 1 CONT 1 CONT We have been shopping, having suits, shoes, bags, etc., made and tomorrow 1 CONC ouor tours and sightseeing starts. This many times postponed trip has 1 CONC been worth waiting for. We love it. 1 CONT 1 CONT Maybelle and Paul 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT 14 APR. Tues. A.M. 1 CONT 1 CONT Dear Anne and Justin: 1 CONT 1 CONT We've been home a week from our "Holiday" and still trying to catch up on 1 CONC my correspondence. 1 CONT 1 CONT Hong Kong is outstanding and we [thoroughly] enjoyed all of it--shopping, 1 CONC sightseeing and eating. 1 CONT 1 CONT Paul had a suit, slacks, sport jackets and shoes made--Beautiful English 1 CONC woolens. I had a suit, coat, couple of silk blouses and shoes made. 1 CONT 1 CONT We traveled with Doc and Liz Seeley--he's senior medical officer at the 1 CONC dispensary--same building with dental clinic. They are young--early 1 CONC 30's, lovely people. Two hospital Drs. and wives were on the trip, too. 1 CONC We all stayed at the Hilton and we all just happened to do our shopping 1 CONC at the same tailors. One nite our tailor invited all of us to a Chinese 1 CONC Night Club for dinner, dancing and floor shows. No tourists, strictly 1 CONC Chinese and it was fabulous. The eight or 10 course dinner was 1 CONC delicious. We probably ate bird's nest soup--unknowingly. 1 CONT 1 CONT One afternoon, we four had a guided tour of Hong Kong and the New 1 CONC Territories. A 6-mile drive through industrial as well as farming areas 1 CONC on up to China Border. We looked over into Red China across a 1 CONC barbed-wire fence. 1 CONT 1 CONT Another morning the four of us chartered the Hilton Yacht with a crew of 1 CONC six and a hostess and toured the harbor areas. Especially enlightening 1 CONC due to the importance of the colony of its waterways. There is only a 1 CONC passenger wharf and all the freight ships tie up at Buous and have to be 1 CONC unloaded by junks. Red China ships are allowed in but have to be 1 CONC unloaded and on their way by nightfall. Ate lunch at floating Sea Palace. 1 CONT 1 CONT There was so much to do and see that we never ate dinner before 9:30 or 1 CONC 10 P.M. 1 CONT 1 CONT They have fabulous restaurants and hotel dining rooms wheere they light 1 CONC fires beside the table and serve " flaming, sizzling" etc. Usually there 1 CONC were four or five waiters constantly hovering over the four of us. Very 1 CONC de luxe service and we revelled in it--you would, too. Paul was glad he 1 CONC wasn't a gourmet. 1 CONT 1 CONT After a week in Hong Kong, we flew Cathay Pacific to Manila. Red Carpet 1 CONC Flight--cocktails, wines with our dinner, after dinner drinks, smokes, 1 CONC etc. 1 CONT 1 CONT We stayed at the Manila Hotel--very old-- but filled with atmosphere-- We 1 CONC enjoyed our guided tour of the city--and saw Walled City where all the 1 CONC Japanese atrocities have left their marks. 1 CONT 1 CONT The Chinese cemetery where millions of dollars are spent for vaults that 1 CONC look like very fashionable homes and apt. buildings with Iron grill work 1 CONC antrances. Many have gardeners and most are air conditioned. All for 1 CONC their ancestors-- quite a religion!! 1 CONT 1 CONT We spent one night at Clark Air Force Base, about 70 mi from Manila and 1 CONC lew home Pan Am 707 Jet. 1 CONT 1 CONT Paul had a scare last day in HK--claims he felt like there was no 1 CONC tomorrow. Dr. Seeley wasn't concerned. Paul needs a lot of rest and 1 CONC apparently wasn't getting enough; however, he did try and nap every 1 CONC afternoon but there were many interruptions. He finally heard from the 1 CONC Bureau and they gave him limited duty--which is what he was hoping foand 1 CONC which means to sea duty or overseas (like Guam) duty but whether they 1 CONC will send him back to the States before Feb--when this tour is ended 1 CONC remains to be seen. A Dr. at the hospital has the same thing but he 1 CONC finished his tour. Guess we will have to wait for further word from the 1 CONC Bureau. 1 CONT 1 CONT Ann announced we will have another grandchild in Sept. to greet us when 1 CONC we return to the mainland. They are building and hope to be in by Xmas-- 1 CONT 1 CONT The Monahan house has been sold and they have to move/May. The Board 1 CONC insists Pat lives in Mazo and there isn't anything desirable or they 1 CONC would have moved before now. Anyway, Lois is busy packing boxes again. 1 CONT 1 CONT The Captain will be home soon for lunch, and I usually have it ready so 1 CONC he can get a 45 minute nap-- 1 CONT 1 CONT Write and let us know how you two are behaving. 1 CONT 1 CONT All our Love, 1 CONT 1 CONT Paul and Maybelle 0 @I0028@ INDI 1 NAME Walbert O. /Nelson/ 2 SOUR @S04038@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT Date of Import: Nov 3, 1999 2 SOUR @NI0074@ NOTE 1 CONC Anne C. (Spellman) Leahy 1 CONT Grandma Leahy was a lot more fun and a lot more tolerant than Grandpa 1 CONC Leahy was. She always wanted to know what we were doing, and how well we 1 CONC liked our various activities. She encouraged art and music. She was 1 CONC quite good in both. But of all her various skills, the one I marveled at 1 CONC the most was her knitting. If she were sitting in a chair (other than 1 CONC one at the dining table) she had her needles out and was knitting. I 1 CONC don't think I ever wore a sweater she didn't make until I was in high 1 CONC school. (Some of them, of course, were hand-me-downs, but it didn't 1 CONC matter). 1 CONT After they moved to Omaha and Grandpa Leahy died, Grandma showed me 1 CONC a tea set (it was porcelain with black outsides covered by a large dragon 1 CONC and yellow inside). She said Grandpa Leahy had gotten it in China while 1 CONC he was in the service. She asked me what I thought of it. And I told 1 CONC her it was really pretty cool. She put it away, and I didn't think about 1 CONC it again until Mom gave me a box that had my name written on it in 1 CONC Grandma's distinctive script. Inside was that tea set. I keep thinking 1 CONC I am going to bring it to the Antiques Roadshow the next time it's in 1 CONC town (I missed it the last time) just to see if it's worth anything. I 1 CONC keep it in a glassed front cabinet. Funeral services were 1 CONC held this Wednesday at Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic Church in Dobie and 1 CONC burial was made in the church cemetery. 1 CONT 1 CONT Mr. Leahy was born Feb. 28, 1918 at Milwaukee and married the former 1 CONC Bette Mullaney on June 21, 1945 at Park Falls. After graduation from St. 1 CONC Thomas College in St. Paul, he attended the University of Chicago, and 1 CONC later Marquette University in Milwaukee where he received his doctorate 1 CONC of jurisprudence. He practiced law at Park Falls where he also served as 1 CONC city attorney and veteran's service officer for Price County for a number 1 CONC of years. He then practiced law in the Twin Cities area until 1967, when 1 CONC he moved to Bloomer and taught high school for several years prior to 1 CONC moving to Rice Lake. He served as a professor of psychology at UW 1 CONC Center-Barron County in Rice Lake until retiring in 1978 because of 1 CONC health problems. 1 CONT 1 CONT In addition to being a United States Navy veteran of World War II he was 1 CONC a member of the Rice Lake Rotary Club, Lions Club, Elk's Lodge, Wisconsin 1 CONC Bar Assn., various education associations, Barron County Campus 1 CONC Foundation and the Heritage Club of Lakeview Medical Center in Rice 1 CONC Lake. In 1972 he was voted one of the Outstanding Educators in the 1 CONC United States and in 1973 he was named Teacher of the Year by the 1 CONC students at UW Center-Barron County. 1 CONT 1 CONT He is survived by his wife Bette, one daughter, Jeanie Foshay of Scandia, 1 CONC Minn; three sons, Thomas of Stillwater, Patrick of Cornell, and Michael 1 CONC of Madison; 10 grandchildren; and three stepgrandchildren. 1 CONT 1 CONT (The identical obituary appeared in the Park Falls Herald on the same 1 CONC day.) 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT from the St. Paul Pioneer Press, November 2, 1983 1 CONT 1 CONT Funeral services for Justin R. Leahy, 65, a former St. Paul lawyer and 1 CONC University of Wisconsin-Barron County professor who died Sunday in Rice 1 CONC Lake, Wis., will be at 11 a.m. today at Our Lady of Lourdes Catholic 1 CONC Church in Dobie, Wis. 1 CONT 1 CONT Born in Milwaukee, he graduated from the College of St. Thomas and then 1 CONC earned his law degree at Marquette University following Navy service in 1 CONC World War II. 1 CONT 1 CONT He specialized in title insurance in St. Paul from 1957 - 66 and taught 1 CONC briefly in Bloomer, Wis., before joining the UW-Barron County Campus 1 CONC faculty as a psychology professor. He retired in the mid 1970s. 1 CONT 1 CONT He is survived by his wife Bette, three sons, Patrick of Cornell, Wis., 1 CONC Michael of Madison, Wis., Thomas of Stillwater, a daughter Jeanie Foshay 1 CONC of Scandia, and 13 grandchildren. Burial will be in the church cemetery. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT From the University of Wisconsin Center System "CENTERSCOPE," November 1 CONC 14, 1983 1 CONT 1 CONT Justin R. Leahy, retired professor of English and Psychology at the 1 CONC University of Wisconsin Center/Barron County, died on Sunday, October 30. 1 CONT 1 CONT Professor Leahy joined the ranks of college teaching later in his 1 CONC professional life after successfully practicing law and teaching high 1 CONC school English. 1 CONT 1 CONT Born in Milwaukee, Leahy received his B.A. from the College of St. Thomas 1 CONC in 1941 and his J.D. from Marquette University in 1947. He worked for 1 CONC ten years in Park Falls in the general practice of law and served as City 1 CONC Attorney and Price County Veteran's Services Officer. In 1957, he moved 1 CONC to White Bear Lake, Minnesota and specialized in title insurance and 1 CONC mortgage banking law. 1 CONT 1 CONT Leahy started his career in education at Bloomer High School where he was 1 CONC an English instructor for three years before joining the Barron County 1 CONC Campus in 1969. 1 CONT 1 CONT Voted "Teacher of the Year" in the early 1970's, the Barron students 1 CONC thought of Dr. Leahy as a caring person and even those who had not taken 1 CONC his courses often sought his counsel. 1 CONT 1 CONT After his retirement, Professor Leahy continued to aid students through 1 CONC the donation of his personal library, consisting of 554 books and A-V 1 CONC materials, to the campus library. In 1983 he and his wife Bette, also a 1 CONC campus employee, set up a special fund to be awarded to needy students on 1 CONC a non-academic basis. 1 CONT 1 CONT He is survived by his wife, Bette, and four children. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT this letter to the editor written by Jim Patraw, a friend and colleague, 1 CONC appeared in the November 10, 1983 Rice Lake Chronotype. 1 CONT 1 CONT "Just in Tribute" 1 CONT 1 CONT Last Wednesday was a day that typified the season of the year - the sky 1 CONC was leaden and overcast, threatening at any moment to open up and fill 1 CONC the rain gauges. The landscape below it was fast taking on the drab 1 CONC colors of a dying harvest season. All things considered, November 2, 1 CONC 1983 spoke of post-summer let-down and pre-winter doldrums. 1 CONT 1 CONT But there was one thing strangely out of place on last Wednesday - a soft 1 CONC warm breeze that blew in from the southwest. For those who have visited 1 CONC Ireland, it made the day feel almost like a soft summer Irish day … and 1 CONC it played a song in the treetop branches of the giant pines that stand in 1 CONC Our Lady of Lourdes Cemetery at Dobie … played a song for and on a circle 1 CONC of people standing around a flag-draped coffin that held the mortal shell 1 CONC of a good Irish man who had gone home. 1 CONT 1 CONT It was no accident that the warm southwest wind was blowing on last 1 CONC clouded-over Wednesday … that good Irish man was a warm wind that would 1 CONC make the most miserable weather seem bearable - even enjoyable. No 1 CONC matter how black and bleak was the overcast or the forecast, the sun was 1 CONC always out when Justin Robert Leahy was sitting in your corner of the 1 CONC world. 1 CONT 1 CONT To his many friends, he was "Doc," and his students at the Barron County 1 CONC Campus called him that with a mixture of respect and affection. Using 1 CONC the full word never seemed to set too well with him. I made the mistake 1 CONC once early on by addressing him as "Doctor," and I was immediately 1 CONC informed by him that he had no license to practice medicine and that 1 CONC "Doc" or "Bob" would do just fine. 1 CONT 1 CONT And "Doc" did just fine … and he practiced medicine of a kind and with a 1 CONC finesse and skill that inspires lesser men to formulate theories and 1 CONC write doctoral dissertations on the methods that just came to him 1 CONC naturally. But knowing these ivory-tower inhabitants as I do, it will 1 CONC take them thirty thousand words, 423 diagrams and six reams of 1 CONC statistical analyses to attempt to analyze his five-word 100 percent 1 CONC effective prescription: "Love your neighbor as yourself." 1 CONT 1 CONT He was an extraordinary person who genuinely felt that everyone was 1 CONC extraordinary. Whether it was the psychology class in Ritzinger Hall, 1 CONC Room 129 in the administration building, over a cup of coffee in the 1 CONC student center, a get-together at Clam Lake, or just a chance meeting 1 CONC anywhere, the light shined bright and the breeze was soft and warm when 1 CONC "Doc" was there … and he was always there for those truly down and out on 1 CONC their luck who needed a helping hand and to talk to who would listen. He 1 CONC would talk with you, not down at you, suggest alternatives rather than 1 CONC deliver dogmas, and when the encounter was over, you were left with the 1 CONC good feeling that you played the major role in solving your own problems 1 CONC - which was a big part of the 100 percent effective prescription. 1 CONT 1 CONT His last few years of earthly tenure were at times very trying for him 1 CONC because of the limitations put on his spirit by a mortal shell that was 1 CONC suffering mechanical breakdown, but there was plenty of steel beneath his 1 CONC velvet and he stayed as long as he could until on the day before this All 1 CONC Hallow's Eve, when the Maker of All decided that it was time for "Doc" 1 CONC Leahy to come home. 1 CONT 1 CONT The mortal shell will be reduced to the atoms of its chemistry, the 1 CONC wooden box that holds it will go the same route, and the slab of stone 1 CONC marking the geographic coordinates of the first two will be the last to 1 CONC realize their same fate, but "Doc" Leahy still lives on in those of us 1 CONC who were fortunate enough to have known and loved him … and I'm sure that 1 CONC he would suggest that we keep the warm breeze blowing soft, the light on 1 CONC and the door open … passing out that 100 percent effective prescription. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT Eulogy delivered at Our Lady of Lourdes Church on November 2, 1983 by Dr. 1 CONC Wayne W. Arntson, a friend and colleague 1 CONT 1 CONT In the fall of 1973 a young black man from Africa, a student at the 1 CONC Barron County Campus, was being overwhelmed by problems: He was in a 1 CONC strange land, the language was different, his funds were running low, and 1 CONC he was having difficulties with the immigration authorities. It was at 1 CONC this moment that Bob Leahy entered the young man's life. 1 CONT 1 CONT No one knows exactly what happened. It is known that Bob drove the young 1 CONC man to Milwaukee for a visit with immigration officials. And it is known 1 CONC that the two spent considerable time together. And it is known that the 1 CONC problems seemed to disappear. It is a fact that two years later the 1 CONC youngster completed his work at the Barron County Campus and was awarded 1 CONC an associate degree. Bob Leahy once again had quietly solved a student's 1 CONC problem. 1 CONT 1 CONT That incident was typical of Bob. He was exceptionally skilled at 1 CONC overcoming problems - and he had plenty of his own to solve. 1 CONT 1 CONT Consider his own health: Bob joined the Navy following Pearl Harbor but 1 CONC contracted rheumatic fever and was discharged in 1943. By 1945 he had 1 CONC recovered enough to marry and attend law school at Marquette University. 1 CONC In 1947 Bob was graduated from Marquette and began his practice which 1 CONC continued into the 60's until heart problems caused him to slow down. 1 CONC Again he bounced back and went to work teaching high school English in 1 CONC 1967 and finally came to our campus in 1968. 1 CONT 1 CONT We're all familiar with Bob's breathing problems that developed in his 1 CONC last few years. They eventually became so severe that the only way he 1 CONC could move from one building to another was to use his little electric 1 CONC cart. He didn't like it and he had no words of endearment for that cart; 1 CONC I recall one incident in which the cart was acting up - I was surprised 1 CONC to discover from Bob's comments that the cart had a dog for a mother. He 1 CONC hated that cart! But, since it was the only way he could meet his 1 CONC students, he used it. He was a man who solved problems. 1 CONT 1 CONT Looking back through old school papers, Twigs, it is a surprise to 1 CONC remember the great turmoil in the late 60's and early 70's: Drugs were 1 CONC rampant; Viet Nam debates continued hot and heavy. In the midst of all 1 CONC the turmoil were many veterans on campus who had special problems of 1 CONC their own. Bob was in the right place. He could help. 1 CONT 1 CONT Bob had a special knack for spotting troubled souls and he could talk to 1 CONC anyone on practically any topic. He had such a variety of interests. The 1 CONC first time I met Bob I discovered a lawyer, teaching high school English, 1 CONC and taking a physics course on our campus. He could speak intelligently 1 CONC on many subjects. 1 CONT 1 CONT But what Bob did mostly was listen and that's what his students needed. 1 CONC Oh, he would offer counsel and advice when asked, but he didn't impose 1 CONC his comments on anyone. Furthermore, it was not at all unusual for him 1 CONC to slip some cash to a downtrodden student. And he always had time - 1 CONC afternoon, evening, 2:00 A.M. - You got a problem? Call "Doc"! He was 1 CONC always there - as you might expect from a man who once termed our campus 1 CONC "the home of beautiful people." 1 CONT 1 CONT Look at some of the campus projects in which Bob was a major influence: 1 CONT The first Earth Day. Remember? 1 CONT The Future 101 class. Highly successful the first few years. 1 CONT The Clam Lake excursions. Students and faculty brought together in 1 CONC a new setting. 1 CONT Clam Lake was Bob Leahy. 1 CONT Major contributions by the Leahys to the College Foundation, 1 CONC including a recent fund 1 CONT to be used by students with "special problems." 1 CONT Over 450 books donated to the library. 1 CONT 1 CONT The one project of which Bob was the proudest? His family. His wife, 1 CONC the perfect partner, and his children whom he rightly called "mature, 1 CONC compassionate, and independent." 1 CONT 1 CONT At a time like this it is fitting that we recall Bob's accomplishments, 1 CONC but perhaps the best tribute we can give him is to carry on his 1 CONC unfinished work. Having learned from his example, let us try to make 1 CONC this a better world. 1 CONT 1 CONT Bob wrote of his students, "I have found that my understanding of them is 1 CONC essential to their success and enjoyment." That applies to everybody, 1 CONC every day. 1 CONT 1 CONT Bob wrote of his own life, "It'll never make the best seller list even 1 CONC though it is loaded with prurient passages, has the greatest plot, and 1 CONC has the best cast of characters ever assembled in a story, but my life in 1 CONC the teaching profession is the most absorbing tale I hope ever to 1 CONC encounter." 1 CONT 1 CONT Well done, thou good and trusted servant. 1 CONT 1 CONT Hail! and farewell. 1 CONT 1 CONT ================================== 0 @I0087@ INDI 1 NAME Timothy O. /Monahan/ 2 SOUR @S04038@ 3 DATA 4 TEXT with many diverse 1 CONC interests. In football, he liked the Green Bay Packers and the Chicago 1 CONC Bears and, of course, the Fighting Irish of the University of Notre 1 CONC Dame. And he disliked teams with an equal intensity, such as the 1 CONC University of Nebraska Cornhuskers. We had a natural rivalry with the 1 CONC Cornhuskers. He always told me I didn't know any better. And I always 1 CONC rooted against the Bears just to give him a hard time. It was more fun 1 CONC to watch a game when we didn't root for the same teams. 1 CONT When I was in high school, Dad and I, and Gramma Vant, when she was 1 CONC in town, would often share a late night cup of coffee and maybe something 1 CONC to go with it (especially when Gramma Vant was in town). We would 1 CONC half-listen to the news and Johnny Carson, and talk. The one thing I 1 CONC learned from him is that nothing should be taken too seriously. That 1 CONC philosophy probably explains why he was so gentle and compassionate. And 1 CONC why he could laugh at himself with such ease. And those are the 1 CONC qualities in him I most admire and try (yes, I do try) to emulate. 1 CONT Dad said the Irish like to tease those they love. And he liked to 1 CONC tease all of his children and his wife and his parents and in-laws. He 1 CONC always did it with a twinkle in his eye. Foster 1 CONT 1 CONT We learn that Mr. John Foster, in the town of Freedonia, was kicked by a 1 CONC horse last Saturday in the barn of Chas. Sands in Random Lake. While a 1 CONC saddler was fitting a collar to one of his horses, having a sore breast, 1 CONC John was standing behind the horse when it kicked and struck him in the 1 CONC abdomen, from which injury he died Monday morning [9 JUN 1883], John had 1 CONC a good many friends in this county who feel sorry for his sad misfortune. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT Death of John Foster of Random Lake 1 CONT 1 CONT It is a source of regret to the many friends of Mr. John J. Foster, of 1 CONC Random Lake, to learn of his painful and rather sudden death on Tuesday 1 CONC from the effects of a kick received from a horse on the 7th [of June 1 CONC 1883]. The deceased was born in Pennsylvania, and came to Wisconsin in 1 CONC 1856 and settled in the township of Freedonia, Ozuakee County, where he 1 CONC has ever since been successfully engaged in farming. As a Catholic he 1 CONC lived in accordance with the teachings of the Church and performed many 1 CONC acts of charity and kindness. By his death, the cause of temperance loses 1 CONC a zealous advocate. In his last moments, he was tended by Rev. Father 1 CONC Hamm, who administered the consolations of the Church. He leaves a wife 1 CONC and eleven children, five sons and six daughters, to mourn his untimely 1 CONC death. May his soul rest in peace. 1 CONT 1 CONT --probably from a Random Lake newspaper 1 CONT [from papers of Anne C. One of the projects she became quite involved 1 CONC in after her husband died was the funeral support services of her 1 CONC church. At the time of her husband's death, the church did not provide 1 CONC as much support to the families as it does now, and I think my mother 1 CONC would be proud of the difference she made in that area of the church's 1 CONC ministry. 1 CONT In the kitchen, Mom was a gadget person. I once told her I was 1 CONC going to invent the electric fork for her, which I thought was 1 CONC hysterically funny at the time (I think I was a freshman in High 1 CONC School--so I was pretty impressed with everything I did then). She 1 CONC didn't think much of that idea, but she did like her other toys: She had 1 CONC special dishes for every conceivable kind of food preparation, and 1 CONC mechanical devices to help with the same. There was the noodle maker and 1 CONC salad spinner, the electric juicer, the dehydrater, the magic meal 1 CONC sealer.... And all of the toys were marvelous to behold, but they sure 1 CONC took up a lot of room in the kitchen. When I came home from college on 1 CONC breaks, the counters would be covered with the contraptions. And, I 1 CONC would make the mistake of putting them away. The next morning, she 1 CONC needed almost everything brought back out for some project or another. 1 CONC What she needed was a bigger kitchen. If she had had the space, I think 1 CONC my mother would have gladly catered any function anyone wanted to put 1 CONC on. Mom's forte was dessert: cookies, cakes and pastries (we won't 1 CONC mention the prune torte, as every cook is entitled to a few items that 1 CONC don't quite make the grade...). 1 CONT The one thing I would have wished for Mom was more forgiving sense 1 CONC of self. Miss Martha Foster aged sixteen died 1 CONC Saturday evening at the home of her mother, one and one-half miles 1 CONC south-west of this village. She had not been in good health for several 1 CONC weeks, but not until a half hour before she died did her relatives begin 1 CONC to realize that the end was near. It seems hard to realize that she is 1 CONC dead, she was a highly accomplished young lady and a general favorite 1 CONC with all. Among her friends the deceased will be sadly missed especially 1 CONC by the members of St. Mary's Choir in which she was a leading member. The 1 CONC funeral took place Monday forenoon from the family residence, the remains 1 CONC were taken to St. Mary's Catholic Church where the services were 1 CONC conducted by Re. Father Miller, after which a large concourse of friends 1 CONC followed the cortege to Mount Calvary cemetery where the remains were 1 CONC laid to rest. 1 CONT 1 CONT * * * 1 CONT 1 CONT Once again the members of the Foster family are chilled by a strange 1 CONC stillness for a member has passed stealthily through the dark halls. A 1 CONC heavy shadow fell from the wing of death as its unbaffled voice called 1 CONC and demanded from our midst our youngest sister, a gentle girl of sixteen 1 CONC summers. At six o'clock in the Evening (Easter Saturday), after a short 1 CONC illness, Martha quietly breathed hew soul into the arms of her maker. In 1 CONC our sorrow we wonder why one so young and gifted should be snatched from 1 CONC the world she had not yet learned to know. But while we leave this with 1 CONC the many mysteries that must remain unsolved in this live [we] can but 1 CONC repeat the words, "Thy will be done on earth as it is in Heaven." 1 CONT 1 CONT When we say that she was a good girl, we say but little that might be 1 CONC said of her gentle disposition and manner, always more thoughtful of 1 CONC others than of herself. None knew how but to love her, and she will be 1 CONC missed by her family and host of friends. She was a member of the choir 1 CONC and Young Ladies Sodality of St. Mary's congregation, and the place that 1 CONC she filled among them can never be filled by another that by itself shows 1 CONC how deeply her loss is realized. The cause of her death was that dreaded 1 CONC disease, pneumonia, turning into heart trouble. She had been sick only 1 CONC three weeks and apparently grew better the last week even speaking of 1 CONC joining the family for the Easter Greeting on the morrow, the morrow 1 CONC which was never to come for her. All that could possibly be done to save 1 CONC her was done by kind and loving hands. But all earthly power and medical 1 CONC skill having failed, God called her for His own. 1 CONT 1 CONT Why do we mourn departing friends, the question is easily answered, we 1 CONC miss them so. A noble young girl has gone home and will be there to 1 CONC welcome others as they come. Deceased was attired in her First Communion 1 CONC suit, her long and curly hair hanging over her shoulders, a smile on her 1 CONC face seemed to say she was only sleeping. The funeral services were held 1 CONC Monday from St. Mary's church by. Rev. Mueller it being one of the 1 CONC largest ever held in this parish. The body was laid to rest besides those 1 CONC of her father, who died when she was in her third year, and her sister, 1 CONC Mary, who proceeded her in death by over seven years. 1 CONT 1 CONT Among those from abroad who followed the remains to the last resting 1 CONC place were Mr. and Mrs. William Downey of Antigo, Mr. Thomas Bradley and 1 CONC daughter Maggie of Newburg, Mr. Jno. O'Brien, Mrs. M. Rilley and 1 CONC daughters Aggie and Lizzie, Misses Jennie and Annie O'Brian, Miss Mary 1 CONC Rilley, of Milwaukee, and Jas. And Nellie Mooney of Brown Deer, besides a 1 CONC host of friends who came to pay their last tribute to all that was left 1 CONC of their dear friend and school mate. The pallbearers were Thos. Hand, 1 CONC Jno. Arends, C. D. Malloy, Will Rheingans, Willie McCafrey and Andrew 1 CONC Arends. Besides her mother, she leaves to mourn her loss five brothers 1 CONC and four sisters, Mrs. P. J. Foster, 824 3rd Street, Milwaukee. 1 CONT 1 CONT The deceased young gentleman was only twenty-four years of age, and had 1 CONC been for four years a student of St. Francis' Seminary, where his 1 CONC brilliant intellect and aptitude for learning had enabled him to run one 1 CONC year ahead of his studies. His sunny disposition and gentlemanly conduct 1 CONC won for him the esteem of his classmates, and his strict compliance with 1 CONC the discipline of his superiors made him the college favorite. But, alas, 1 CONC for the profession in which he would have shone as a twinkling luminary, 1 CONC and for the home that was made ethereal by his presence, they are both 1 CONC bereft of their priceless jewel. Hard study and close application 1 CONC undermined his youthful constitution and left him an easy prey for the 1 CONC grim reaper, who makes no distinction between young and old, worker or 1 CONC drone. In hopes of recuperating he bent his steps westward to the climate 1 CONC of golden sunset and invigorating breeze, only to find that his earthly 1 CONC sojourn was fast coming to a close. His anxious friends, learning that 1 CONC the western climate was powerless to bring about his much-desired 1 CONC recovery, besought him to return home, that they might be able to comfort 1 CONC him in his last moments, or, perchance, alleviate the pain of his 1 CONC feverish brow. Accordingly, Dr. J. J. Foster, examining physician of our 1 CONC division, went to Mexico and brought him back to breathe his last in the 1 CONC bosom of his family and dearest friends. 1 CONT 1 CONT Thus ended in life's roseate morn the career of a brilliant and promising 1 CONC Irishman. His death leaves a void that cannot be easily filled in the 1 CONC hearts of his parents and friends, who are prostrate with grief at the 1 CONC loss of their darling boy. Let us that Time, the great healer of sorrows, 1 CONC will supply the balm for the wound his death so unexpectedly inflicted in 1 CONC their loving hearts. His exemplary life is a guiding star for all who 1 CONC desire to tread the narrow path of virtue and uprightness. To his 1 CONC bereaved family and our esteemed brother, Dr. J. J. Foster, we tender 1 CONC heartfelt sympathy in the heavy affliction that has befallen them. 1 CONT 1 CONT The large concourse of mourners that followed the remains to their last 1 CONC resting place, Random Lake, testified to the high esteem in which the 1 CONC deceased was held. The deceased was 54 years 1 CONC of age and has resided in the city for over sixteen years. He was born in 1 CONC Cleveland, Ohio, March 27, 1857 and moved from Oshkosh to this city 1 CONC during the year of 1895. Mr. Spellman, while beating a Brussels carpet at 1 CONC his home on South Van Buren street, a week ago last Friday afternoon, 1 CONC rubbed the skin off the knuckle of his little finger on his right hand. 1 CONC Not paining him in any way he paid no attention to it, but the following 1 CONC Friday, he was taken to St. Vincent hospital for treatment for the 1 CONC scratch, but in spite of all medical attention, he passed to his reward 1 CONC last evening at 10 o'clock. He was a very prominent man in the city and 1 CONC was widely known by many citizens. He was a candidate for alderman on the 1 CONC social democratic ticket in the Fifth ward at the spring election. 1 CONC Besides his many well known friends and relatives he leaves his wife, one 1 CONC son and one daughter, with his mother and three brothers to mourn his 1 CONC loss. His mother resides at Milwaukee with her sons, James and William, 1 CONC the other brother is a resident of Green Lake. The funeral services over 1 CONC the remains will be conducted Wednesday forenoon at 8 o'clock from St. 1 CONC John's schoolhouse. Leahy 1 CONT Grandpa Leahy had a stern visage and, from a kid's point of view, a mean 1 CONC demeanor. My oldest brother, Jim, said he wasn't always like that. He 1 CONC even remembered Grandpa Leahy playing ball in the yard when he was 1 CONC young. But I don't have any of those memories. I remember his paying me 1 CONC (and my brothers and sisters-lest you think I was the only one to make 1 CONC noise) to be quiet or go outside and play. I remember the gold mine my 1 CONC middle sister Janet found when Grandpa and Gramma came down for Christmas 1 CONC the year she had the chicken pox or measles. She's lie on the couch and 1 CONC groan just loud enough to distract Grandpa from whatever show he was 1 CONC watching, and he would pay her a quarter to stop! 1 CONT I know Grandpa liked football and baseball. And he and Grandma 1 CONC Leahy both golfed. But the thing I remember most is his sitting in a big 1 CONC armchair at his house or ours and reading the paper from cover to cover. 1 CONC And not wanting to be bothered by anyone while he did it. Not me. Not 1 CONC Dad. Not even Grandma!--RMLeahy 1 CONT ___________ 1 CONT 1 CONT 1 CONT Personal knowledge; notes and scrapbooks of Anne C. Vant in 1945, after 1 CONC the death of her first husband, Karl Bernard Lillestrand (1942). And she 1 CONC was known to my brothers and sisters and me as Gramma Vant. Gramma Vant 1 CONC was fun. She enjoyed life and she wanted everyone around her to enjoy 1 CONC it, too. 1 CONT When I was very little, the family packed up for two weeks in the 1 CONC summer and headed for Minneapolis. Back then, Irel Vant was still 1 CONC working (he ran a trucking company), and he got up early. Gramma got up 1 CONC even earlier to get breakfast going for him. All of us kids would be 1 CONC asleep in the living room. Gramma would make her way into the kitchen 1 CONC and turn the light on over the sink. Then she would turn the tap on the 1 CONC get water for coffee. That was my cue to get up. I would step over 1 CONC brothers and sisters and make my way to the kitchen, and I would watch 1 CONC Gramma chop potatoes and cook pork chops or bacon. When the coffee was 1 CONC ready, she would give each of us some in a big mug. And we would sit and 1 CONC watch the sky brighten and drink our coffee. We whispered some, but not 1 CONC much, because Gramma didn't want us to wake anybody else up--although I 1 CONC don't know how any of them slept through frying bacon and percolating 1 CONC coffee. Once Grampa Vant got up, everyone else did, too. Grampa Vant 1 CONC didn't know how to do things quietly.... 1 CONT Gramma Vant's two major cooking tasks for us were lefse and her 1 CONC little dinner rolls. I'm afraid the secret to her dinner rolls left the 1 CONC earth with her. I've never been able to duplicate them, and Jody tried 1 CONC to figure out the recipe by watching Gramma whip them up and was never 1 CONC able to get the exact recipe. 1 CONT After Grampa Vant retired, they travelled more. And they played a 1 CONC lot of cards. Thirty-one and cribbage were favorites. 1 CONT One of Gramma Vant's greatest abilities was in sewing. She could 1 CONC whip out dresses and shirts faster than anybody I ever saw. She made 1 CONC almost every dress I ever saw her wear until she was well into her 1 CONC nineties. 1 CONT In the last year or so of her life, I think her biggest 1 CONC disappointment was her loss of sight. Not only because she could no 1 CONC longer see the people around her, but because she could no longer work 1 CONC her word puzzles. Lydia Had Memorable Times 1 CONT Lydia Gosch lived 86 interesting and satisfying years, possibly 1 CONC because she early learned to take and to overcome the hardships life gave 1 CONC her. 1 CONT By the time she was 16 growing up in rural Selby, she had lost both 1 CONC of her parents and became the stand-in mother for her two younger 1 CONC brothers and three younger sisters. An avid musician and vocalist, her 1 CONC aspirations to become a guitarist and country singer were cut short. 1 CONT During the years she and her husband, Frank Gosch, Jr., had their 1 CONC farm near Selby, they were host to the famous movie actor, Robert Taylor 1 CONC for at least two hunting seasons. 1 CONT A daughter, about 5 or 6 at the time, remembered, "Mom took his 1 CONC visits in stride like everything else, she was always so easy going." 1 CONT "Whenever she was away from home, she was homesick and couldn't wait 1 CONC to get back and have the family about her." 1 CONT In May of 1998, Lydia and Frank moved to the Prairie Sunset Village 1 CONC in Mobridge. She had a neart attack early in November and was released 1 CONC to the Beverly Healthcare Center in Mobridge where Frank shared her room. 1 CONT Lydia died at the center Dec. 10, 1999, at the age of 86. 1 CONT She was born Jan. 23, 1913, in Selby, the fifth child born to George 1 CONC and Christine (Sulzle) Sulzle. Her father was a photographer and 1 CONC farmer. She attended a one-room school in the Kennedy School District 1 CONC where she obtained an eighth grade diploma. 1 CONT On Aug. 15, 1936, Lydia and Frank Gosch, Jr., of Selby, were 1 CONC married. Together they purchased the Sulzle farm which they operated 1 CONC until 1983 to New Evans Resort on the banks of the Oahe southeast of 1 CONC Mobridge. From 1965 to 1967, they also operated the Twilight Motel and 1 CONC Cafe in Glenham. 1 CONT She was a member of St. Jacobi Evangelical Lutheran Church (WELS) in 1 CONC Glenham, the church Ladies' Aid, the Busy Bee Extension Club and Cane 1 CONC Creek Extension Club. She loved gardening, music and children, and she 1 CONC was always there for the children. 1 CONT She leaves her husband, Frank, who has returned to Prairie Sunset 1 CONC Village; four sons and their wives, Lester and Edna Gosch of Mobridge, 1 CONC Dale and Beverly Gosch and Kennith and Ardys Gosch, all of Aberdeen, and 1 CONC Dean and Linda Gosch of Selby; two daughters and their husbands, Connie 1 CONC and Ronald Hepper of Mobridge and Marie and Tim Ranek of Yankton; one 1 CONC daughter-in-law, Connie Gosch of Glenham; 33 grandchildren, 45 great 1 CONC grandchildren, and one great great grandchild, Michael; and one sister, 1 CONC Kathtren Setran of Lubbock, Texas. 1 CONT In addition to her parents, George in 1928 and (unreadable) in 1929, 1 CONC Lydia was preceded in death by her son, Eugene in 1976, two 1 CONC granddaughters, Linsay and LaRae Gosch, a great grandson, her sisters 1 CONC Minnie, Emma, Selma, Ida and Christina, and her brothers Andrew and twins 1 CONC Art and Adolph. 1 CONT Funeral servives for Lydia were Tuesday at Zion Evangelical Lutheran 1 CONC Church in Mobridge. The Reverand Peter J. Naumann officiated. 1 CONT Organist was Barbara Naumann. The congregation sang, "My Hope Is 1 CONC Built on Nothing Less," "Just as I am" and "Asleep in Jesus." The 1 CONC children's choir sang, "Silent Night." 1 CONT Casket bearers were Frank Eugene Gosch, John Braun, Clark Hepper, 1 CONC Donavan Gosch, Andre Gosch, Grant Gosch and Stanley Schulz. All of 1 CONC Lydia's grandchildren were honorary bearers. 1 CONT Burial was at Glenham Cemetery under the direction of the Kesling 1 CONC Funeral Home of Mobridge. 1 CONT A family service was held The following is taken from same source (and 1 CONC page): "The O'Brien Family is descended from Milesius, King of Spain, 1 CONC through the line of Heber, third son of that monarch. The founders of 1 CONC the family were Brian Borimbhe, or Boro, King of Ireland, 1002-1014AD, 1 CONC and Moriertach O'Brien, last King of Ireland, of the race Brian Boro, 1 CONC 1089 AD. Through their descent from Cormac Cas, son of Ollum, King of 1 CONC Munster, 177, and his consort, Sabia, daughter of Con of the Hundred 1 CONC Battles, King of Ireland, 148 AD, the blood of Heber and Heremon is 1 CONC united in this family. The ancient name was Brian, signifying "The 1 CONC Author." The titles of the chiefs of the clan were Prince of Thomond, 1 CONC and King of Cashel and Munster. Their possessions were located in the 1 CONC present counties of Cork, Limerick and Clare. Most of the Kings of 1 CONC Munster were of the O'Brien Branch. From this stem sprung all the 1 CONC nobility and gentry of Munster." 1 CONT 1 CONT Tairdelbach [alias Turlough O'Brien (A.D. 1009 to 1086)], King of Munster 1 CONC [an ancient kingdom and historic province in Ireland that occupies the 1 CONC southwestern portion of the Republic of Ireland], was the grandson of 1 CONC Brian Boru(mha). [Brian Boru became chief king of Ireland in A.D. 1002, 1 CONC but was slain after a victory over the Danes at Clontarf, near Dublin, in 1 CONC A.D. 1014. "Bill" O'Brien 1 CONT Bill of the O'Brien Run, Old Mail Clerk, Passes 1 CONT 1 CONT When William M. (Bill) O'Brien, 88, died Tuesday [11 APR 1939] at his 1 CONC home, 1518 Wauwatosa av., Wauwatosa [, WI], an unusual chapter in the 1 CONC records of the federal government was closed, it was revealed Friday. In 1 CONC 1888 Bill O'Brien became a railway mail clerk. From then until 1923, when 1 CONC he retired, he plied the railroads in Wisconsin, sorting and stamping 1 CONC mail. In 1894 Alfred O'Brien, a son, also became a railway mail clerk and 1 CONC he also retired in 1937 after 43 years' service. Thus the government had 1 CONC father and son on pension at the same time. That was a most unusual 1 CONC situation according to government records. 1 CONT 1 CONT Bill O'Brien was born in the town of Granville, Milwaukee county, in 1 CONC 1850, into a family which had settled there in 1838. His first run as a 1 CONC mail clerk was between Chicago and Minneapolis on the Milwaukee road. The 1 CONC trip took 14 hours. The number of that train was, and still is, 57, but 1 CONC the run today is made in six and one-half hours. 1 CONT 1 CONT After eight years Bill O'Brien was shifted to the Milwaukee-Mineral Point 1 CONC run, and it was on this route that he became so well known that railroad 1 CONC men called it the "Bill O'Brien run." He sorted mail for 20 years between 1 CONC here and Mineral Point. He was one of the first men to come under the 1 CONC federal pension plan. 1 CONT 1 CONT Funeral services were held Friday [14 APR] morning at the J. N. O'Boyle 1 CONC funeral chapel, 1214 W. Wisconsin av., and later at St. Bernard's church. 1 CONC Burial was in Holy Cross cemetery. Leahy of this city. 1 CONT To the strains of the Lohengrin Wedding March the bride approached 1 CONC the altar on the arm of Mr. Vant who gave her in marriage. She was 1 CONC attired in an Autralian green suit with a hat and veil to match and her 1 CONC flowers were white orchids. 1 CONT Mrs. I. J. Laconik served as the matron of honor for the bride. She 1 CONC was attired in a deep purple suit with a hat to match and wore lavender 1 CONC orchids. 1 CONT Lt. Leahy selected Lt. I. J. Laconik, a classmate at Notre Dame, as 1 CONC his best man and guests were ushered to their places by Lts. George 1 CONC Porter and Thomas Boldt. 1 CONT On the main altar, before which the double ring service was read, 1 CONC were large vases of white asters, white gladioli, and tuberoses and huge 1 CONC baskets of the same flowers were on either side of the chancel rail. 1 CONC During the ceremony, a soloist sang Schubert's "Ave Maria" and the organ 1 CONC played softly throughout the service. 1 CONT After the ceremony, the bridal party proceeded to the Mangor Hotel, 1 CONC where the young couple received the congratulations of their friends. At 1 CONC noon, a wedding breakfast was served to 20 guests in the Rennaissance 1 CONC Room. The breakfast table was beautifully decorated with white flowers, 1 CONC huge silver candelabra with white tapers and as a cenbterpiece, a large 1 CONC wedding cake. 1 CONT Mrs. Leahy is a graduate of St. Andrew's Hospital, Minneapolis, and 1 CONC spent a year and a half at Wesley Hospital in Chicago before entering 1 CONC service as a Lieutenant in the ANC. She was in service sixteen months, 1 CONC fourteen of which were spent overseas, and returned from France the 1 CONC latter part of June, when she received her discharge. 1 CONT Lt. leahy is a graduate of St. Thomas Military Academy, receiving 1 CONC his bachelor of Science degree from Notre Dame and his Doctor of Medicine 1 CONC from Northwestern. He is now stationed temporarily at Brooks General 1 CONC Hospital, Fort Sam Houston, and the young couple will reside in San 1 CONC Antonio until Lt.
